You are being asked to take part in a research study on how comfortable people feel answering trivia questions. Please read this carefully and ask any questions you may have before conducting the survey.

 

Should you choose to participate you will be asked a series of questions as well as how confident you are in each of your answers. These questions will consist of discerning whether a statement is true, and expressing how confident you feel about your choice. We will then ask you to evaluate phrases, solve word puzzles, and describe your personality.

 

There are no known risks associated with participating in this survey, other than those encountered in day-to-day life. Participation is voluntary, and you are free to discontinue the survey at any time. This will in no way negatively impact your current or future relationship with Princeton University or any of the associated study personnel. Your answers will not be associated with your identity in any way and will be completely anonymous.

 

You email address will not be stored with any of your question results, and only one entry per subject is possible.

 

If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me at josephbb@princeton.edu or the Princeton Institutional Research Board at irb@princeton.edu. By clicking "Start Survey" you acknowledge that you have read through this information, are aware of the risks and consent to take part in the survey.

SS_Squash: A game of squash can be played either to 9 or to 15 points (that is, the game can either end when one of the two squash players scores 9 points, or it can end when one of them scores 15 points). Holding all other rules of the game constant, if A is a better player than B, which scoring system will give A a better chance of winning?
GF1_Slot: When playing slot machines, people win something about 1 in every 10 times. Julie, however, has just won on her first three plays. What are her chances (out of 10) of winning the next time she plays?
DenNeglect: Assume that you are presented with two trays of black and white marbles: a large tray that contains 100 marbles and a small tray that contains 10 marbles. The marbles are spread in a single layer on each tray. You must draw out one marble (without peeking, of course) from either tray. If you draw a black marble, you win $2. Consider a case in which the small tray contains 1 black marble and 9 white marbles, and the large tray contains 8 black marbles and 92 white marbles. From which tray would you prefer to select a marble in a real situation?
ProbMatch: A die with 4 red faces and 2 green faces will be rolled 60 times. Before each roll you will be asked to predict which color (red or green) will show up once the die is rolled. You will be given one dollar for each correct prediction. Assume that you want to make as much money as possible. What strategy would you use in order to make as much money as possible by making the most correct predictions?
Num1: Imagine that we roll a fair, six-sided die 1000 times. Out of 1000 rolls, how many times do you think the die would come up as an even number?
Num2: In the BIG BUCKS LOTTERY, the chances of winning a $10.00 prize are 1%. What is your best guess about how many people would win a $10.00 prize if 1000 people each buy a single ticket from BIG BUCKS?
Num3: Which of the following numbers represents the biggest risk of getting a disease?
